{{Infobox feature on celestial object |name = Ezinu |image = File:PIA19065-Ceres-DwarfPlanet-Dawn-OpNav9-image1-20150523.jpg |caption = Ezinu (top) and [[Nawish (crater)|Nawish]] (bottom) |type = |location = [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] |coordinates= {{coord|43.15|N|195.43|E|globe:ceres_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} |coordinates_footnotes = <ref name="GPN">{{cite web |author=Staff |title=Planetary Names: Crater, craters: Ezinu on Ceres |url=http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/15336 |date=6 July 2015 |work=[[USGS]] |accessdate=7 August 2015 }}</ref> |length = |width = |diameter = {{convert|119.93|km|mi}} |depth = |area = |dimensions = |peak = |discoverer = |naming = After the Sumerian goddess of grain |eponym = }}
'''Ezinu''' is a large crater on [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]]. It was officially named by the [[International Astronomical Union|IAU]] on July 3, 2015 and being one of the second row of names of a Cerean crater, <ref name="GPN"/> and named it after the [[Sumerian mythology|Sumerian]] goddess of grain.<ref name="GPN"/>
Nearby prominent craters include [[Kaikara (crater)|Kaikara]] to the east, [[Nawish (crater)|Nawish]] to the south and [[Ialonus (crater)|Ialonus]] to the northwest. Nearly halfway between the crater and Nawish is [[Junina Catenae]]. South of the crater is [[Hanami Planum]].
[[File:Ezinu and Nawish craters in context.jpg|thumb|center|Ezinu and Nawish craters in context]]
